{
  "text": "Even though the thymus undergoes physiologic atrophy with age, T cells are generated and incorporated into the peripheral T cell pool in adulthood, albeit at slower rate than in children [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Thymectomy or thymic dysfunction in early life has been shown to cause premature aging of the immune system in humans [CITATION_5] , as well as enhanced autoimmunity in mice [CITATION_6] . Moreover, loss of thymic activity in adults has been shown to reduce oral tolerance [CITATION_7] and to hamper the affinity maturation of antibodies [CITATION_8] . Loss of thymic T cell output in adults has more obvious consequences when peripheral lymphopenia occurs concomitantly as it is the case in AIDS patients [CITATION_9] .",
